{"parentUuid":"bb03dc01-289e-400f-a501-6742ff679d4a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"a75f31bf3a7b0d04a","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DYV4C6ykixUjWtyfq8ZK74","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# DGC Terminal Interface — Definitive Component Architecture\n     2→\n     3→**Version:** 1.0  \n     4→**Date:** 2026-03-05  \n     5→**Target:** Python Textual 8.0.2 + Claude Code CLI v2.1.69 `--output-format stream-json`  \n     6→**Platform:** macOS M3 Pro, Python 3.14  \n     7→**Status:** Architecture Blueprint — Ready for Implementation\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Table of Contents\n    12→\n    13→1. [Question 1: Architecture Tradeoffs](#q1-architecture-tradeoffs)\n    14→2. [Question 2: TUI Design Patterns Worth Stealing](#q2-tui-design-patterns-worth-stealing)\n    15→3. [Question 3: Textual 8.0.2 Best Practices](#q3-textual-802-best-practices)\n    16→4. [Question 4: Missing Features & Gaps](#q4-missing-features--gaps)\n    17→5. [Question 5: Future-Proofing for Self-Evolution](#q5-future-proofing-for-self-evolution)\n    18→6. [Question 6: Complete Component Architecture](#q6-complete-component-architecture)\n    19→7. [Appendix A: Claude Code NDJSON Protocol Reference](#appendix-a-claude-code-ndjson-protocol-reference)\n    20→8. [Appendix B: Warm Dark Theme Specification](#appendix-b-warm-dark-theme-specification)\n    21→9. [Appendix C: Research Sources](#appendix-c-research-sources)\n    22→\n    23→---\n    24→\n    25→## Q1: Architecture Tradeoffs\n    26→\n    27→### The Core Question\n    28→\n    29→> \"Monolith `tui.py` vs decomposed package — how do we split 1,600 lines into the right module boundaries for a self-evolving system?\"\n    30→\n    31→### Verdict: Decomposed Package with Hard Boundaries\n    32→\n    33→The current 1,600-line `tui.py` monolith is **the single biggest impediment** to both DGC's self-evolution and developer velocity. Here's why and how to fix it.\n    34→\n    35→### Recommended Package Structure\n    36→\n    37→```\n    38→dgc/tui/\n    39→├── __init__.py              # Public API: DGCApp class only\n    40→├── app.py                   # DGCApp(App) — 150 lines max\n    41→├── screens/\n    42→│   ├── __init__.py\n    43→│   ├── main.py              # MainScreen — primary workspace\n    44→│   ├── session_browser.py   # SessionBrowserScreen — history nav\n    45→│   ├── settings.py          # SettingsScreen — config editor\n    46→│   └── help.py              # HelpScreen — contextual help overlay\n    47→├── widgets/\n    48→│   ├── __init__.py\n    49→│   ├── stream_output.py     # StreamOutputWidget — main chat/output\n    50→│   ├── prompt_input.py      # PromptInput — multi-line TextArea\n    51→│   ├── thinking_panel.py    # ThinkingPanel — extended thinking\n    52→│   ├── tool_call_card.py    # ToolCallCard — individual tool call\n    53→│   ├── task_list.py         # TaskListWidget — telos/todo tracking\n    54→│   ├── status_bar.py        # StatusBar — model, cost, context %\n    55→│   ├── mode_indicator.py    # ModeIndicator — N/A/P mode display\n    56→│   ├── file_tree.py         # FileTreeWidget — context file browser\n    57→│   ├── diff_viewer.py       # DiffViewer — inline/side-by-side diffs\n    58→│   └── session_card.py      # SessionCard — session list item\n    59→├── engine/\n    60→│   ├── __init__.py\n    61→│   ├── stream_parser.py     # NDJSON parser — zero UI dependency\n    62→│   ├── subprocess_manager.py# Claude Code process lifecycle\n    63→│   ├── session_state.py     # Session state machine\n    64→│   └── event_types.py       # Dataclass models for all events\n    65→├── theme/\n    66→│   ├── __init__.py\n    67→│   ├── dharma_dark.py       # DharmaDark(Theme) — warm amber\n    68→│   └── dharma_dark.tcss     # TCSS stylesheet\n    69→└── commands/\n    70→    ├── __init__.py\n    71→    └── palette.py           # CommandPalette providers\n    72→```\n    73→\n    74→### Why This Structure\n    75→\n    76→| Decision | Rationale |\n    77→|----------|-----------|\n    78→| **`engine/` has zero Textual imports** | The stream parser and subprocess manager are pure Python. They can be unit-tested without any TUI, used by Darwin Engine for non-interactive runs, or replaced entirely. This is the most critical boundary. |\n    79→| **One widget per file** | Each widget is independently evolvable. Darwin Engine can mutate `stream_output.py` without touching `prompt_input.py`. `grep -l` finds exactly where any behavior lives. |\n    80→| **Screens as composition, not behavior** | Screens only `compose()` widgets and handle routing. All logic lives in widgets or engine. This prevents the \"God Screen\" anti-pattern. |\n    81→| **Theme is a separate concern** | TCSS files + Theme subclass. Agents can restyle the entire app by editing `dharma_dark.tcss` without touching Python. |\n    82→| **Commands are separate** | CommandPalette providers are pure data — easy to extend, test, or auto-generate. |\n    83→\n    84→### Tradeoff: Speed of Refactor vs Clean Architecture\n    85→\n    86→You could do this incrementally:\n    87→\n    88→1. **Phase 1** (2 hours): Extract `engine/stream_parser.py` and `engine/event_types.py` from the monolith. This gives you testable event parsing immediately.\n    89→2. **Phase 2** (4 hours): Extract each widget into its own file. The monolith becomes a thin `compose()` shell.\n    90→3. **Phase 3** (2 hours): Introduce Screens, theme, and command palette.\n    91→\n    92→**Do not try to rewrite from scratch.** Extract, don't rewrite.\n    93→\n    94→### Message Bus Architecture\n    95→\n    96→The fundamental data flow pattern:\n    97→\n    98→```\n    99→Claude Code subprocess (NDJSON stdout)\n   100→        │\n   101→        ▼\n   102→┌─────────────────────┐\n   103→│  SubprocessManager   │  Thread worker: reads lines, posts messages\n   104→│  (engine layer)      │\n   105→└────────┬────────────┘\n   106→         │ post_message(AgentEvent)\n   107→         ▼\n   108→┌─────────────────────┐\n   109→│  DGCApp / Screen     │  Routes events to widgets\n   110→└────────┬────────────┘\n   111→         │ Message bubbling / queries\n   112→         ▼\n   113→┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n   114→│  Widgets: StreamOutput, ToolCallCard, TaskList,  │\n   115→│  StatusBar, ThinkingPanel, DiffViewer            │\n   116→└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n   117→```\n   118→\n   119→**Key principle:** `SubprocessManager` emits typed `Message` subclasses. Widgets subscribe via `on_*` handlers. No widget ever touches the subprocess directly.\n   120→\n   121→---\n   122→\n   123→## Q2: TUI Design Patterns Worth Stealing\n   124→\n   125→### Competitive Analysis Summary\n   126→\n   127→After analyzing 9 tools (Aider, Open Interpreter, Goose, Claude Code CLI, k9s, lazygit, bottom, Warp, Toad), here are the patterns that matter most for DGC:\n   128→\n   129→### 1. lazygit's Command Log (STEAL THIS FIRST)\n   130→\n   131→lazygit shows a scrollable log of every `git` command it executes. This is the single most powerful trust-building pattern in any TUI.\n   132→\n   133→**DGC adaptation:** A \"Tool Call Log\" panel that shows every tool invocation Claude makes, with:\n   134→- Tool name + input summary (collapsed)\n   135→- Expand to see full input/output\n   136→- Duration + success/failure badge\n   137→- Click to jump to the chat context where it was invoked\n   138→\n   139→```\n   140→[10:42:01] Bash: pytest tests/ → ✓ 12 passed (3.2s)\n   141→[10:42:05] Edit: routes.py → ✓ +8/-2 lines (0.1s)\n   142→[10:42:06] Read: config.yml → ✓ 45 lines (0.0s)\n   143→[10:42:09] Bash: git diff → ✓ (0.8s)\n   144→```\n   145→\n   146→### 2. k9s's `:resource-type` Navigation Grammar\n   147→\n   148→k9s uses a consistent `:type` pattern: `:pods`, `:deploy`, `:svc`. This creates a learnable navigation grammar.\n   149→\n   150→**DGC adaptation:** Use `/` for filtering (like k9s) and `:` for screen navigation:"}]},"uuid":"f3b7d142-69c6-4ee2-9d3f-829195e5596a","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:32.553Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bb03dc01-289e-400f-a501-6742ff679d4a","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
