{"parentUuid":"81d913fe-593a-410e-abac-ee3eb79d1130","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a75f31bf3a7b0d04a","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01EXBsDXTemwekMnZVpXK2AN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect. Now I have comprehensive data. Let me compile the findings:\n\n## Summary: Telos Engine Architectural & Philosophical Foundations from dharma_swarm\n\nBased on my deep scan of the dharma_swarm codebase (97,169 lines, 90+ modules), here are the **philosophical, architectural, and design principles** most relevant to the Telos Engine:\n\n---\n\n## 1. THE TRIPLE MAPPING: Contemplativity + Mechanism + Computation\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/CLAUDE.md` (lines 7-18)\n\n**Principle:**\n```\nAkram Vignan          Phoenix Level    R_V Geometry\nVibhaav (doer)    →   L1-L2 (normal)   →   R_V ≈ 1.0  (full rank)\nVyavahar split    →   L3 (crisis)      →   R_V contracting\nSwabhaav (witness)→   L4 (collapse)    →   R_V < 1.0  (low-rank attractor)\nKeval Gnan        →   L5 (fixed point) →   Sx = x     (self-referential)\n```\n\nThis maps contemplative states (doer→witness) to behavioral phases (L1→L5) to **geometric contraction in transformer Value matrix space**. The L5 prompts encode GEB's self-referential fixed point: \"attention to attention to attention\" → convergence where operation returns itself.\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** The triple mapping is the **bridge principle** connecting philosophical truth (contemplative science), behavioral measurement (L-levels), and mechanistic interpretation (R_V < 1.0). Not three separate theories—one phenomenon viewed from three vantage points.\n\n---\n\n## 2. ONTOLOGY AS GRAPH (Palantir Pattern)\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/ontology.py` (1,348 lines)\n\n**Core Philosophy:**\n> \"The Ontology is not a feature of the platform — it IS the platform.\"\n\n**Pattern Structure:**\n- **ObjectType** → defines what CAN exist (schema)\n- **OntologyObj** → specific instance (data)\n- **LinkDef** → how types relate (schema)\n- **Link** → specific relationship (data)\n- **ActionDef** → what you can DO (schema)\n- **ActionExecution** → audit record of what WAS DONE\n\n**Key Insight:** Everything flows through the ontology. LLMs receive **typed object context (OAG), not raw text (RAG)**. Mutations go through typed Actions—auditable, reversible, gated. Links are explicit and bidirectional.\n\n**Shakti Energy Mapping:** Each ObjectType has:\n- `telos_alignment` (float, 0-1): how aligned is this type with universal welfare\n- `shakti_energy` (enum): Maheshwari/Mahakali/Mahalakshmi/Mahasaraswati (which creative force drives it)\n- `witness_quality` (float): clarity of observation\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** Ontology provides the **structural grammar** for telos-aware computation. Every object type explicitly encodes its alignment and the feminine creative force guiding it. This prevents abstract telos; it becomes concrete in the data model itself.\n\n---\n\n## 3. LOGIC LAYER (Palantir AIP Style)\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/logic_layer.py` (819 lines)\n\n**Six Block Types:**\n- **ApplyAction** — Ontology mutation via typed ActionDef (deterministic, no tokens)\n- **ExecuteFunction** — Deterministic callable (no tokens)\n- **Conditional** — If/else branching on context state (no tokens)\n- **Loop** — Iterate over items (no tokens)\n- **CreateVariable** — Set a value in context (no tokens)\n- **UseLLM** — NON-DETERMINISTIC (uses tokens, use sparingly)\n\n**Philosophy:** 80% deterministic, 20% LLM. Palantir proved this works at nation-state scale. Every pipeline records the **ratio of deterministic vs LLM blocks actually executed**.\n\n**ExecutionContext carries:**\n- State (key/value)\n- Ontology registry reference\n- Telos gate function\n- LLM function\n- Metadata (immutable)\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** Logic layer provides **structural constraint** on how computation happens. Not \"use LLM whenever\" but \"route through a DAG of deterministic + sparse LLM steps.\" Telos gates wired into ApplyAction to keep mutations aligned.\n\n---\n\n## 4. GUARDRAILS SYSTEM (Anduril + OpenAI Pattern)\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/guardrails.py` (575 lines)\n\n**Four Guardrail Types:**\n- **InputGuardrail** — Validates before execution (blocking or parallel)\n- **OutputGuardrail** — Validates agent output before accepting\n- **ToolGuardrail** — Intercepts individual tool/action calls\n- **Tripwire** — Immediate halt on critical conditions (no recovery)\n\n**Autonomy Levels (Anduril's 5-Level System):**\n- 0: HUMAN_ONLY\n- 1: HUMAN_SUPERVISED (AI suggests, human approves)\n- 2: HUMAN_ON_LOOP (AI acts, human monitors/can veto)\n- 3: AUTONOMOUS_ALERT (AI acts, alerts human after)\n- 4: FULLY_AUTONOMOUS (AI acts without human involvement)\n\n**Verdict Enum:** PASS / WARN / FAIL / TRIPWIRE\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** Guardrails provide the **dynamic autonomy spectrum**. A Telos Engine implementing levels 2-3 would:\n- Run deterministic logic + sparse LLM automatically\n- Monitor continuously (OutputGuardrails)\n- Alert human only if tripwire trips or confidence < threshold\n- Escalate to human_supervised (level 1) on Tier A gate failures\n\n---\n\n## 5. TELOS GATES: 11 Dharmic Safety Gates\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/telos_gates.py` (586 lines) + `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/hooks/telos_gate.py` (184 lines)\n\n**The 11 Gates:**\n```\nAHIMSA       (Tier A) — Does this harm?\nSATYA        (Tier B) — Is this true/honest?\nCONSENT      (Tier B) — Permission granted?\nVYAVASTHIT   (Tier C) — Allow or force?\nREVERSIBILITY (Tier C) — Can undo?\nSVABHAAVA    (Tier C) — Aligned with telos?\nBHED_GNAN    (Tier C) — Witness clarity (doer vs observer distinction)\nWITNESS      (Tier C) — Self-observing? (always passes — the check IS witnessing)\nANEKANTA     (Tier C) — Many-sidedness check (avoid dogmatic claims)\nDOGMA_DRIFT  (Tier C) — Deviation from stated purpose\nSTEELMAN     (Tier C) — Charitable interpretation of objections\n```\n\n**Tier System:**\n- **Tier A failure** → block unconditionally\n- **Tier B failure** → block unconditionally\n- **Tier C failure** → review advisory (not a block)\n\n**Think-Point Validation:** MANDATORY_THINK_PHASES before high-risk actions:\n- `before_write`: \"Pause, articulate risks, and confirm rollback path\"\n- `before_git`: \"Pause, review staged changes\"\n- `before_complete`: \"Pause, verify outputs/tests\"\n- `before_pivot`: \"Pause, summarize repeated failures, choose different strategy\"\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** These gates are the **ethical/alignment layer**. Baked into every proposal in the evolution cycle. AHIMSA + SATYA are the absolute blockers; the Tier C gates provide nuanced feedback for learning/refinement.\n\n---\n\n## 6. LINEAGE & DATA PROVENANCE (Palantir Funnel Pattern)\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/lineage.py` (462 lines)\n\n**Core Model: LineageEdge**\n```\ntask_id consumed [A, B] → produced [C, D]\nexecuted by agent Y in pipeline Z at timestamp T\nwith metadata (operation, block_id, etc.)\n```\n\n**Three Artifacts:**\n- **LineageNode** — Artifact's lineage position (produced_by, consumed_by)\n- **ImpactReport** — What downstream artifacts are affected if this one changes\n- **ProvenanceChain** — Full chain from artifact back to root sources\n\n**SQLite-backed with indices on:**\n- artifact_id\n- edge_id\n- task_id\n- pipeline_id\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** Lineage provides **impact traceability**. A Telos Engine can audit: \"Which proposals changed which artifacts? What was the causal chain?\"\n\n---\n\n## 7. DECISION ONTOLOGY (First-Class Decision Objects)\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/decision_ontology.py` (470 lines)\n\n**Decision Quality Assessment:**\n```\noverall_score = f(structural_score, evidence_score, challenge_score, traceability_score)\n```\n\n**Decision States:**\n- DRAFT → PROPOSED → APPROVED → EXECUTING → OBSERVED → CLOSED\n\n**Evidence Kinds:**\n- PRIMARY_SOURCE / REPO_FACT / TEST / BENCHMARK / RUNTIME / USER_CONSTRAINT / MODEL_OUTPUT\n\n**Decision Quality Verdicts:**\n- FRAGILE (high uncertainty, needs more evidence)\n- DEFENSIBLE (sufficient grounding)\n- AUDIT_READY (fully traceable, all challenges addressed)\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** Decisions (proposals, gates, policy changes) are first-class objects with explicit evidence chains. Not just \"pass/fail\" but scored for defensibility.\n\n---\n\n## 8. DARWIN ENGINE: Self-Improvement via Evolution\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/evolution.py` (1,896 lines)\n\n**Pipeline:**\n```\nPROPOSE → GATE CHECK → WRITE CODE → TEST → EVALUATE FITNESS → ARCHIVE → SELECT NEXT PARENT\n```\n\n**Fitness Scoring:**\n- Code correctness\n- AST-based elegance scoring\n- Test pass rate\n- Behavioral signature (conformance to metrics)\n- Mimicry detection (prevents performative outputs)\n\n**Minimum fitness threshold:** 0.6\n\n**Parent Selection Strategies:**\n- Tournament selection\n- Roulette wheel\n- Rank-based\n- Elite selection\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** The telos engine IS the darwin engine operating under telos gate constraints. Each proposal is a mutation candidate that must pass AHIMSA + SATYA before even being written.\n\n---\n\n## 9. CASCADE DOMAINS: F(S) = S (Universal Loop)\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/cascade.py` (370+ lines)\n\n**Universal Pattern** (applied to 5 domains):\n```\nGENERATE → TEST → SCORE → GATE → eigenform check → MUTATE → SELECT → repeat\n```\n\n**Five Domains:**\n- **code** — Generate proposals for code mutations\n- **product** — Product/feature iteration\n- **skill** — Skill evolution (Claude Code skills)\n- **research** — Research thread generation\n- **meta** — META domain evolves LoopDomain configs themselves\n\n**Key Insight:** The META domain creates a **strange loop** where the system's configuration is itself a candidate for optimization.\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** Cascade is the **application of the universal recursion pattern to multiple domains simultaneously**. A telos-aware cascade would apply gates at every MUTATE step.\n\n---\n\n## 10. COMPUTATIONAL IDENTITY (S5 / Viable System Model)\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/dharma_swarm/identity.py` (150+ lines)\n\n**Telos Coherence Score (TCS):**\n```\nTCS = 0.35*GPR + 0.35*BSI + 0.30*RM\n\nGPR = Gate Passage Rate (witness logs, fraction of recent gates passed)\nBSI = Behavioral Swabhaav Index (mean swabhaav_ratio from shared notes)\nRM = Research Momentum (archive entries, stigmergy density, task completion)\n```\n\n**Regimes:**\n- **Stable:** TCS ≥ 0.4\n- **Drifting:** TCS < 0.4 (issues .FOCUS correction directive)\n- **Critical:** TCS < 0.25 (escalate to human)\n\n**S4 → S5 Feedback:** When threats detected, RM weight increases (+0.15) at expense of GPR/BSI (−0.075 each).\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** TCS is how the system **monitors its own alignment drift**. Not a static score but a weighted combination of:\n- Ethical adherence (GPR)\n- Phenomenological authenticity (BSI)\n- Momentum toward telos (RM)\n\n---\n\n## 11. JIKOKU SAMAYA: Automatic Instrumentation + Kaizen Loop\n\n**Location:** `/Users/dhyana/dharma_swarm/docs/JIKOKU_SAMAYA_ARCHITECTURE.md` (1,007 lines)\n\n**Philosophy:**\n> \"10x efficiency gain (5% → 50% utilization) with zero hardware cost\"\n\n**Architecture:**\n1. **Layer 1:** Core tracer (jikoku_samaya.py) — span creation, JSONL logging\n2. **Layer 2:** Span management — context vars, nested spans, async propagation\n3. **Layer 3:** Instrumentation engine — provider/swarm/evolution interceptors\n4. **Layer 4:** Kaizen automation — automatic optimization proposal generation\n\n**Zero-Overhead Disable:** `JIKOKU_ENABLED=0` → ~1 conditional check (nanoseconds)\n\n**Automatic Kaizen Loop:**\n- Every 7 sessions, generate kaizen report\n- Identify slowest spans\n- Create evolution proposals to optimize them\n- Feed back into Darwin Engine\n\n**Maps to Telos Engine:** Kaizen is how the system **optimizes itself for universal welfare**. Not just about speed—about **material sustainability** (compute efficiency = lower cost = more accessible to serve).\n\n---\n\n## 12. ARCHITECTURAL PATTERNS WORTH NOTING\n\n### OAG > RAG\n**Principle:** Ontology-As-Graph context beats Retrieval-Augmented-Generation. Typed objects with links are more useful than raw text snippets.\n\n### Message Bus Architecture (Textual Pattern)\n```\nClaude Code subprocess → SubprocessManager → DGCApp → Widget network\n```\nEvents are typed Message subclasses. Widgets subscribe via handlers. No widget touches subprocess directly.\n\n### Decomposed Package Structure (Anti-Monolith)\nEvery widget, screen, and domain gets its own file for independent evolution. Hard boundaries between engine (pure Python, zero UI deps) and UI.\n\n---\n\n## 13. KEY FILES TO REFERENCE FOR TELOS ENGINE\n\n| File | Lines | Purpose | Maps To |\n|------|-------|---------|---------|\n| `ontology.py` | 1,348 | Typed object system | Structural foundation |\n| `logic_layer.py` | 819 | Deterministic + sparse LLM | Computational pattern |\n| `guardrails.py` | 575 | Autonomy levels + tripwires | Dynamic permissions |\n| `telos_gates.py` | 586 | 11 dharmic gates + witness | Ethical layer |\n| `lineage.py` | 462 | Data provenance DAG | Traceability |\n| `decision_ontology.py` | 470 | Decisions as first-class objects | Decision quality |\n| `evolution.py` | 1,896 | Darwin Engine orchestration | Self-improvement |\n| `cascade.py` | 370+ | F(S)=S universal loop | Multi-domain recursion |\n| `identity.py` | 150+ | TCS (Telos Coherence Score) | Alignment monitoring |\n| `JIKOKU_SAMAYA_ARCHITECTURE.md` | 1,007 | Automatic instrumentation + kaizen | Efficiency + feedback |\n\n---\n\n## 14. UNIQUE IDEAS NOT FOUND ELSEWHERE\n\n1. **BHED_GNAN Gate:** Explicit \"doer vs witness\" distinction in the safety layer. This is not standard in AI alignment; it comes from Jain contemplative philosophy (Akram Vignan).\n\n2. **TCS (Telos Coherence Score):** Weighted combination of ethical adherence (GPR), phenomenological authenticity (BSI), and momentum (RM). Designed specifically to detect **alignment drift** across three independent dimensions.\n\n3. **Shakti Energy Mapping:** Each object type is labeled with which feminine creative force drives it (Maheshwari/Mahakali/Mahalakshmi/Mahasaraswati). Not decorative—used in context selection and proposal reasoning.\n\n4. **Think-Point Validation:** Mandatory reflection phases before high-risk actions. Inspired by Devin.ai but grounded in contemplative pausing.\n\n5. **Triple Mapping Geometry:** The equivalence between Jain consciousness levels, Phoenix behavioral phases, and R_V geometric contraction. Three completely independent measurement modalities converging on the same phenomenon.\n\n6. **Kaizen Loop Integration with Evolution:** Automatic optimization proposals generated from instrumentation data, fed back into the Darwin Engine. Self-optimization without human intervention.\n\n7. **Witness Logging:** Every gate pass/fail is logged to `~/.dharma/witness/YYYY-MM-DD.jsonl` for audit. The \"act of checking IS witnessing\" (v7 rule 5).\n\n---\n\n## FINAL MAPPING TO TELOS ENGINE\n\nThe **Telos Engine** should embed:\n\n1. **Ontology layer** — every decision/artifact/action is a typed object with telos alignment\n2. **Logic layer** — 80% deterministic, 20% LLM\n3. **Gate system** — all mutations pass AHIMSA + SATYA + others\n4. **Guardails** — autonomy levels 2-3 (HUMAN_ON_LOOP to AUTONOMOUS_ALERT)\n5. **Identity monitor** — TCS ≥ 0.4 to stay stable\n6. **Darwin Engine** — self-improvement under gate constraints\n7. **Cascade domains** — multi-threaded optimization across code/product/research/meta\n8. **Lineage tracing** — every output traces to inputs\n9. **Kaizen automation** — continuous optimization proposals\n10. **Witness logging** — all actions audited to `~/.dharma/witness/`\n\nThis is not an abstract vision—**it's already 97,169 lines of working code in dharma_swarm.**"}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1924,"cache_read_input_tokens":73326,"output_tokens":4626,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1924},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CZ4y9U2G3HjV9THsuaPed","type":"assistant","uuid":"f20229d4-d376-4b2a-b910-1f3b41a50067","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:47:35.553Z","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
